LS(1)                            User Commands                           LS(1)

NAME
       ls - list directory contents

SYNOPSIS
       ls [OPTION]... [FILE]...

DESCRIPTION
       List information about the FILEs (the current directory by
       default).  Sort entries alphabetically unless a sort option is
       given.

OPTIONS
   Listing format:
       -l     use a long listing format

       -1     list one file per line

       -m     list entries separated by commas

       -C     list entries by columns (default for terminal output)

       -x     list entries by lines instead of by columns

       -g     like -l, but do not list owner

       -o     like -l, but do not list group information

       -n, --numeric-uid-gid
              like -l, but list numeric user and group IDs

   File selection:
       -a, --all
              do not ignore entries starting with .

       -A, --almost-all
              do not list implied . and ..

       -d, --directory
              list directories themselves, not their contents

       -B, --ignore-backups
              do not list implied entries ending with ~

       --hide=PATTERN
              do not list implied entries matching PATTERN

       -I, --ignore=PATTERN
              do not list implied entries matching PATTERN

   Sorting:
       -S     sort by file size, largest first

       -t     sort by time, newest first

       -v     natural sort of (version) numbers within text

       -U     do not sort; list entries in directory order

       -f     list all entries in directory order (implies -aU)

       -r, --reverse
              reverse order while sorting

   Display options:
       -h, --human-readable
              with -l and -s, print sizes like 1K 234M 2G etc.

       --si   likewise, but use powers of 1000 not 1024

       -k, --kibibytes
              default to 1024-byte blocks for file system usage

       -s, --size
              print the allocated size of each file, in blocks

       -i, --inode
              print the index number of each file

       -F, --classify
              append indicator (one of */=>@|) to entries

       -p     append / indicator to directories

       --file-type
              likewise, except do not append *

       --color[=WHEN]
              color the output; WHEN can be 'always', 'auto' (default
              if omitted), or 'never'

       -G, --no-group
              in a long listing, don't print group names

       -N, --literal
              print entry names without quoting

       -q, --hide-control-chars
              print ? instead of nongraphic characters

       --show-control-chars
              show nongraphic characters as-is

       -Q, --quote-name
              enclose entry names in double quotes

       --quoting-style=WORD
              use quoting style WORD for entry names: literal, locale,
              shell, shell-always, shell-escape, shell-escape-always,
              c, escape

       --indicator-style=WORD
              append indicator WORD to entry names: none, slash,
              file-type, classify

       --format=WORD
              across (-x), commas (-m), horizontal (-x), long (-l),
              single-column (-1), verbose (-l), vertical (-C)

       --sort=WORD
              sort by WORD: none (-U), size (-S), time (-t), version (-v),
              extension (-X)

       --time=WORD
              change the default of using modification time; access time
              (-u): atime, access, use; change time (-c): ctime, status;
              birth time: birth, creation

       -c     with -lt: sort by, and show, ctime; with -l: show ctime
              and sort by name; otherwise: sort by ctime

       -u     with -lt: sort by, and show, access time; with -l: show
              access time and sort by name; otherwise: sort by access
              time

   Recursive:
       -R, --recursive
              list subdirectories recursively

   Miscellaneous:
       -T, --tabsize=COLS
              assume tab stops at each COLS instead of 8

       -w, --width=COLS
              set output width to COLS. 0 means no limit

       --help display this help and exit

       --version
              output version information and exit

